<h1 id="introduction-to-html" class="title">Introduction to HTML</h1>
<p class="paragraph">HTML stands for Hypertext Markup Language. It was first introduced in <strong>1993</strong> by <strong>Tim Berners-Lee</strong> to share the information world wide. Hypertext Markup Language (HTML) is the standard markup language for creating web pages.</p>
<p class="paragraph">HTML is also known as programming language but technically it is a markup language because it contains no logic.</p>
<h3 id="hypertext" class="subheading">Hypertext</h3>
<p class="paragraph">Hypertext means a text has a link within it is called hypertext, or in simple language information inside information.</p>
<h3 id="markup-language" class="subheading">Markup Language</h3>
<p class="paragraph">Markup commonly means making format changes in a document. In that event the language used by computer to apply formats on a document is recognized as Markup Language. It makes text more interactive and impressive.</p>
<h2 id="brief-history" class="heading">Brief History</h2>
<p class="paragraph">The <strong>first version</strong> of <strong>HTML</strong> was written in <strong>1993</strong> by <strong>Tim Berners Lee</strong>. He wanted to create a technology that would help physicists to share their research analysis and data from anywhere with who they want in the whole world, so he invented a system that store collection of document in one single place. Also make it possible to download and view a document with a single click, this idea results in HTML. HTML is based on <strong>SGML (Standard Generalized Markup Language)</strong> which exists since 1940's but without the ability to link.</p>
<p class="paragraph">He proposed a draft to the <strong>Internet Engineering Task Force (IETF)</strong>, a standards organization. IETF drafts require implementations, so the HTML draft referenced Mosaic, a web browser that later became Netscape, which later became Firefox.</p>
<p class="paragraph">The HTML Working Group was an <strong>Internet Engineering Task Force (IETF)</strong> working group from <strong>1994 to 1996</strong>, and a <strong>World Wide Web Consortium (W3C)</strong> working group from <strong>1997 to 2015</strong>.</p>
<h2 id="html-versions" class="heading">HTML Versions</h2>
<p class="paragraph">HTML has a long life span. It is an evolving language that does not stay same for long, HTML changes with new set of standards with time to make the language easy and more creative for the learners and creators.</p>
<h3 id="html10" class="subheading">HTML1.0</h3>
<p class="paragraph">The first version of HTML is <strong>HTML1.0</strong>. It was first introduced in 1993 for the purpose of sharing information from one place to another using web technologies.</p>
<p class="paragraph">This was the basic Version which support elements like text editing and images, this versions does not support tables, font editing and styling document.</p>
<p class="paragraph">Also at that time the count of web developers was not great as present day, so it affect the growth of language.</p>
<h3 id="html20" class="subheading">HTML2.0</h3>
<p class="paragraph"><strong>Second version</strong> of HTML that was introduced in <strong>1995</strong> with the intention of improving first version of HTML. The second version is titled <strong>HTML2.0</strong>. It contains all the features of HTML1.0 along with additional features like forms development, text boxes, buttons etc. It continue as the standard markup language for website creation till Jan 1997.</p>
<h3 id="html32" class="subheading">HTML3.2</h3>
<p class="paragraph"><strong>Third version</strong> of HTML was <strong>HTML3.2</strong>. It was introduced in <strong>Jan 1997</strong> by <strong>Dave Raggett</strong>. It has better support for new form elements. It includes improved features and more competent characteristics. It also supports <strong>Cascading Style Sheets(CSS)</strong> and frames.</p>
<p class="paragraph">But these competent features slowed down the browser when more improvements are done in the browser.</p>
<h3 id="html401" class="subheading">HTML4.01</h3>
<p class="paragraph"><strong>Fourth version</strong> of HTML was developed in <strong>1999</strong>. It was <strong>widely used</strong> and the <strong>most successful</strong> version of HTML. It introduced the concept of external Cascading Style Sheets.</p>
<h3 id="html5" class="subheading">HTML5</h3>
<p class="paragraph">This is the <strong>latest version</strong> of HTML. It was published in <strong>2012</strong>, which is an extended version of HTML 4.01.</p>
<p class="paragraph">It also added the ability to create applications that function offline.</p>
<h2 id="web-browser" class="heading">Web Browser</h2>
<p class="paragraph">A web browser is an application software used to access information on the WWW (World Wide Web), or in simple words an application that takes you anywhere on the internet world to access documents.</p>
<h2 id="features" class="heading">Features</h2>
<p class="paragraph">HTML is the simplest and productive language made up of elements, which are applied to text portions to give them a completely different meaning in a Document. These elements mention how to display the content on the web browsers.</p>
<ul class="numbers inside">
  <li>HTML is <strong>easy to understand</strong> language.</li>
  <li>It can be <strong>modified easily</strong>.</li>
  <li>It is <strong>independent of platform</strong>.</li>
  <li><strong>Light Weight</strong> in Structure.</li>
  <li>Easily <strong>integrate</strong> with <strong>other languages</strong>.</li>
  <li>HTML is a <strong>markup language</strong>.</li>
  <li><strong>Hypertext supporting</strong> language.</li>
  <li><strong>Instant change in display</strong> when modified.</li>
</ul>
<h2 id="applications-of-html" class="heading">Applications of HTML</h2>
<p class="paragraph">HTML is used for many useful purposes in the web development world.</p>
<h3 id="web-page-structure" class="subheading">Web Page Structure</h3>
<p class="paragraph">HTML is used for making web page structures with the help of HTML tags and elements. With the use of HTML tags and elements the heading, paragraph, forms, tables and other important contents can be defined. It helps in defining the title, heading and sub headings of the document using <code>&lt;h1&gt;</code>, <code>&lt;h2&gt;</code>, <code>&lt;h3&gt;</code> to <code>&lt;h6&gt;</code> tags. <code>&lt;h1&gt;</code> tag make the text font bigger and bold. <code>&lt;h2&gt;</code> tag is also used to make the text bigger and bolder, but size of the text generated by h2 tag is smaller in size as compared to that of h1 tag. These tags can only be applied using HTML, without HTML the document text is all same there is no difference between the title and the paragraph.</p>
<h3 id="navigating-internet" class="subheading">Navigating Internet</h3>
<p class="paragraph">With HTML it would be very difficult task to navigate the internet. HTML <code>&lt;anchor&gt;</code> tags make it easy to link pages to or from the another document. Let's take an example of hyperlink to google</p>
<pre><code class="language-html">&lt;a href=&quot;https://www.google.com&quot;&gt;Google home page&lt;/a&gt;
</code></pre>
<h3 id="images-and-videos" class="subheading">Images and Videos</h3>
<p class="paragraph">HTML also let you embed images and videos in a web page. With the help of HTML one can adjust the width, height and position of the images embedded to the web pages, which make the web pages more presenting and attractive.</p>
<p class="paragraph">Videos controls can also be adjusted using HTML like timestamps, thumbnails, auto play are applied to videos.</p>
<h3 id="game-development" class="subheading">Game Development</h3>
<p class="paragraph">HTML can't create Pure video games but the help of HTML element <code>&lt;canvas&gt;</code> using CSS and JavaScript video games can be build in browser.</p>
<h2 id="simple-html-example" class="heading">Simple HTML Example</h2>
<p class="paragraph">HTML example for creating a simple web page. This program is an introductory program used by HTML learners. Save this code using notepad or any other text editor in a file <code>index.html</code> and open it using any browser of coice such as <code>Google Chrome</code> or <code>Firefox</code> or <code>Safari</code> or any other. You will be greeted by the output similar to the one shown below.</p>
<p class="filename">index.html</p>
<pre><code class="language-html">&lt;!DOCTYPE html&gt;
&lt;html lang=&quot;en&quot;&gt;
&lt;head&gt;
   &lt;title&gt;Introduction&lt;/title&gt;
&lt;/head&gt;
&lt;body&gt;
   &lt;h1&gt;First Example in HTML&lt;/h1&gt;
&lt;/body&gt;
&lt;/html&gt;
</code></pre>
